Help Type: topic
Topic: uri

Wiki Graph URIs

Purpose:
  Wiki Graph commands use URIs as their address format. A URI can point to an archive, a scoped collection, or one object inside an archive.

Archive locator:
  - Archive/object command URIs must contain a `.wikg` locator.
  - Do not pass a bare filesystem path as a command target.
    Use a Wiki Graph URI instead:
    /Users/me/book.wikg -> wkg:///Users/me/book.wikg
    ./book.wikg -> wkg://book.wikg
  - Absolute archive locators use `wkg:///`:
    wkg:///books/book.wikg
  - Relative archive locators use `wkg://`:
    wkg://book.wikg
    wkg://books/book.wikg
  - The first path segment ending in `.wikg` is the archive/object boundary.

Short object URIs:
  Commands return short object URIs without local file paths:
    wkg://chapter/3
    wkg://chapter/3/source/
    wkg://chapter/3/source#4..8
    wkg://chapter/3/summary
    wkg://chunk/12
    wkg://entity/Q8018
    wkg://triple/Q8018/discusses/Q123
    wkg://triple/Q8018/_/Q123

Located object URIs:
  Add an archive locator before the object path when passing a URI to a command:
    wkg:///books/book.wikg/chapter/3
    wkg:///books/book.wikg/chapter/3/source#4..8
    wkg://book.wikg/entity/Q8018
  Returned short URIs are archive-relative handles, not complete command targets. Prepend the archive locator before passing them back to object commands.
  Located readable object URIs can omit the `get` verb:
    wikigraph wkg://book.wikg/entity/Q8018
  Collection and lens URIs still require an explicit verb such as `list` or `search`.

Triple pattern lenses:
  Use `_` as an any-value placeholder for subject, predicate, or object:
    wkg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/_/Q123
    wkg://book.wikg/triple/_/_/Q123
  Trailing placeholders may be omitted:
    wkg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018
    wkg://book.wikg/triple/Q8018/discusses
  A complete triple URI without `_` is a concrete object, not a collection lens.

Object command examples:
  Search an absolute local archive:
    wikigraph wkg:///Users/me/book.wikg/entity search "keyword" --limit 20 --json
  Open an object inside an absolute local archive:
    wikigraph wkg:///Users/me/book.wikg/entity/Q8018 get

Archive command examples:
  Create or inspect an archive:
    wikigraph wkg://book.wikg create ./book.md
    wikigraph wkg://book.wikg/chapter list --all --jsonl
    wikigraph wkg://book.wikg/chapter/tree get --json

Job URIs:
  Queue jobs use the `wkg-job://` scheme and do not contain `.wikg` locators:
    wikigraph wkg-job:// list
    wikigraph wkg-job://<job-id> get --json
    wikigraph wkg-job://<job-id> watch --jsonl

Scopes:
  - `wkg:///book.wikg` addresses the whole archive.
  - `wkg:///book.wikg/` is the same archive target; a trailing slash does not create a separate object.
  - `wkg:///book.wikg/chapter/3` scopes search and list to chapter 3.
  - `wkg:///book.wikg/entity` searches or lists archive-level entities.
  - `wkg:///book.wikg/chapter/3/entity` searches or lists entities scoped to chapter 3.
  - `wkg://chapter/3/entity/Q8018` is the entity view whose evidence must appear in chapter 3.

Object boundaries:
  - `chapter` is a structural object; searching it uses chapter title and structure, not child source or summary text.
  - `source` is the evidence endpoint. `evidence` is not available for source or chapter objects.
  - `summary`, `chunk`, `entity`, and `triple` can return source-backed evidence.
